# 8. この手に掴んだもの

Tsukasa: (The hunter's words compel the monster to take a hard look at himself.)
Tsukasa: (At creature that does not belong.)
Hunter: “It's transformed into a human and is currently masquerading around as one of you. However, its true nature is fundamentally inhuman.”
Monster: “Right...”
Monster: “I love to have fun. That's why I do things humans view as dangerous, or even hurt people.”
Monster: “That's what I've been doing until now. I may look like a human now, but I haven't actually changed.”
Monster: “But that is just who I am.”
Monster: “I was born this way. How do you change that?”
Monster: “I...”
Monster: “I didn't want to be born a monster.”
Sakaki: (For a scene like this, normally you'd have the actor rage and weep, or else visibly struggle to repress his emotions...)
Rui: For this scene, I'd like you to refrain from showing strong emotion.
Tsukasa: Refrain from it? What do you mean?
Rui: In this scene... The monster is feeling a deep sense of despair regarding his own existence.
Rui: He can't run from who he is. He can't change his fundamental nature, either.
Rui: No matter how much he kicks and screams, he'll never be like those around him.
Rui: He knows that better than anybody else.
Tsukasa: (He's never had someone who can understand him. And that loneliness has been his only, constant companion.)
Tsukasa: (He thought he'd come to terms with it already... But he finds himself at a crossroads here.)
Monster: “It was only ever a matter of time until I hurt Master or the people of this city...”
Monster: “Which means it might be time to leave. Tonight.”
Monster: “But...”
???: “Hold it.”
Monster: “Hunter... Out hunting monsters this late at night? You're certainly dedicated.”
Hunter: “Yes, I am... And now I've finally pinned you down.”
Hunter: “Humans don't go walking around on moonless nights without even a lantern to light the way, after all.”
Monster: “...”
Hunter: “I will end you here. To avenge all the innocents you have harmed, monster.”
Monster: “Hahaha! Is that so...! I might actually be okay with that.”
Monster: “If my death will bring peace, then it's a small cost to pay.”
Minstrel: “Please, wait!”
Monster: “M-Master?! Why are you here?”
Minstrel: “Why wouldn't I be here?! Anyone would be worried if their apprentice was acting really strange!”
Hunter: “Please, step aside.”
Hunter: “That thing is not your apprentice. Merely a monster wearing a human face.”
Minstrel: “He might be a monster, but he's also my valued apprentice.”
Minstrel: “And a budding minstrel with the ability to make people smile.”
Monster: *Wince* “I...”
Hunter: “What nonsense.”
Hunter: “Does this mean you're willing to take responsibility the next time this monster harms another person?”
Minstrel: “I...!”
Monster: “It's true. No ordinary human would be able to stop me.”
Monster: “When I find something fun, I can't stop myself. I prioritize my own desires over everything else.”
Monster: “So, when that happens...”
Monster: “You can shoot me dead, then and there.”
Hunter: “What...?”
Monster: “I will always be a monster. That will never change.”
Monster: “Still, even so...”
Monster: “If there are those who will accept me, even knowing that I'm a monster...”
Monster: “Then, I'd like to stay here.”
Monster: “Yes, you are right. I have caused harm to others.”
Monster: “I never cared about them. If we could never understand each other, it didn't matter what I did to them. But...”
Monster: “Now, seeing people smile as I sing makes my chest feel warm.”
Monster: “I've become motivated to do better next time and surprise them with how good I've gotten.”
Monster: “I... Care about these humans now.”
Hunter: “A monster like you has no business uttering such words.”
Monster: “I know you don't believe me. But I am telling the truth.”
Monster: “I'll do anything to convince you. If you need me to pay a price, then you can take one of my eyes, legs or anything else.”
Monster: “So, please... Won't you give me a chance?”
Minstrel: “P-Please, I also beg you!”
Nene: (The hunter has her own beliefs...)
Nene: (Changing her mind won't be easy. Which is why...)
Hunter: “You aren't fooling me.”
Minstrel: “A gun...!”
Hunter: “An eye or a leg, you said? Neither of those will be enough to make up for your crimes.”
Hunter: “Begone.”
Monster: “Guh...!!”
Hunter: “You're not dodging? Next, it won't be just your leg. I'll be aiming for your heart.”
Minstrel: “P-Please, stop! You'll kill him!”
Monster: “No, Master, it's okay.”
Monster: “I'll take as many shots as I need to convince her.”
Hunter: “...!”
Monster: “Kill me if you feel you must. You're right that things will be much more peaceful once I'm gone.”
Hunter: “You...”
Hunter: “Show me your leg. I'll treat the wound.”
Monster: “What...?”
Hunter: “There is no way for me to know if a monster like you can have a conscience. Or if you truly intend to change your ways.”
Hunter: “So, I will set up camp near this city.”
Hunter: “I shall stay until I see that you are able to keep your word.”
Monster & Minstrel: “...!”
Minstrel: “♪———— ♪————”
Minstrel: “That's the end of the monster's story.”
Monster: “The monster who struggled to change his ways continued to live amongst the humans, but what happened next, nobody knows.”
Monster: “This story probably doesn't end with a happily ever after.”
Minstrel: “But one thing is for certain...”
Monster: “He's no longer alone.”
Veteran Director: Hmm... This definitely wasn't what I was expecting.
Sakaki: Me neither. Honestly, I expected him to give us something straight down the mainstream.
Tom: <“Conceptually, it's a fairytale that adults can also enjoy.”>
Tom: <“The depiction of the lonely, selfish monster's growth, as well as the humanity of those who interact with him, felt so real.”>
Veteran Director: I agree. But having this shown at ArcLand...
Tsukasa: Hmm... They seem to be having a lively discussion regarding what they just saw.
Nene: Yeah, but I can't hear what they're saying...
Emu: Oh, they're waving us over!
Rui: I think that means they're finished. I'll head over now.
Veteran Director: Ahem. Thank you for your patience. We'll begin announcing our thoughts regarding your show.
Rui: I'm ready.
Veteran Director: First, we all gave your detailed portrayal of the psychological aspects of this show very high marks.
Veteran Director: Despite the fairytale setting, you had the audience experience the protagonist's unfair reality and the resulting loneliness and internal conflict he felt.
Veteran Director: However, this was also where opinions split most sharply.
Rui: I understand.
Sakaki: Frankly, some sections were a little too raw to attach ArcLand's name to this.
Sakaki: You got together some nice ingredients, but didn't quite cook them properly.
Rui: I see.
Tom: <“Yes, it felt unbalanced in many ways.”>
Tom: <“But I liked it overall. It was sincere, passionate, and very compelling.”>
Rui: “Thank you very much.”
Rui: “This workshop has taught me so many different things.”
Rui: “This time around, I wasn't able to strike the proper balance with my audience's demands...”
Rui: “But I promise to apply this experience to my next show.”
Tom: <“Hehe. There's no need to rush.”>
Tom: <“You've got a long lifetime of shows ahead of you, after all.”>
Tom: <“Just as today's show was a wonderful expression of everything you've experienced up until now...”>
Tom: <“Moving forward, I'm sure you'll be able to go deeper and deeper. I'll be looking forward to seeing what that results in, Rui.”>
Rui: “Thank you. I'll do my best.”
Tsukasa: Based on his expression, I think he's happy with their assessment.
Nene: Yeah.
Sakaki: ...
???: So, this Kamishiro kid... He got what I was trying to say?
Ohara: He did. But he mainly works on stage productions.
Ohara: The same as you. Which means you'll probably cross paths someday.
Sakaki: Bravo, Kamishiro.
Sakaki: This is going to get very interesting.
